fields.text:
I have begun my Django journey by going through Python Crash Course's 3rd project for web applications. This section of the book is an introduction to Django where we create a Learning Log application (an online journal system that lets
you keep track of information you’ve learned about particular topics).

I've learned that the three main basic points to remember are to:

1.create a URL
2.create a view function that is used by the URL
3.create a template that is populated by the view function

Now, I have to keep going, continue learning and become more comfortable with the Django framework.

I began going through the Udemy Python & Django FullStack video series and decided to return to the Django intro in the book Python Crash Course.

Note that I will be returning to this video series; and, possibly, one, or more, video series for Python and Django in the future.

I am also interested in Python Network Programming; and began a video series offered by Udemy for this subject. After successfully completing the Python section of the series, and before beginning the network programming portion of the series, I decided to start an another Udemy offering for Python & Django Full Stack Development. The reason for this was to become comfortable, and reacquaint myself, with current web development standards (specifically HTML5 and CSS).

My decision, moving forward, will be what do I focus on? 

1.Django to create my personal site and show off my skills as a potential Network Engineer (ie. network programming, cisco, IoT, etc.)

2.Or, Django to create my personal site and show off my skills as a potential Web Developer

Regardless of my decision of which to focus on, and of which career path I take, my ultimate goal is to be able to work remotely.
Still alot of work to do for my "Learning Log" app, but time to start learning about Django Project / Application Deployment using Heroku.

On Sunday (Dec.09th/2018) morning, I completed my initial deployment of the Django Learning Log App to Heroku.

Looks like the database structure from my local Django (default) Sqlite3 database was migrated to Heroku's PostgreSQL database, but without the data!!!

I was also able to complete Django Blog App; and it is ready for deployment to Heroku.

After my initial investigation, migrating my existing SQLite3 database data to Heroku's PostgreSQL database will take me a little longer than expected.

Need to research further and do some testing....

For my future Django Apps, I might use PostgreSQL databases in my local development so that migrations can include the test data, if need be.

OKAY !!! Gonna do this the hard way. Copy and paste all "Topics" and "Entries" from my local Django Learning Log App to my Live Learning Log App on Heroku.

NEVER AGAIN !!! I SHOULD BE ABLE TO INCLUDE THAT DATA DURING THE MIGRATION !!!

PostgreSQL database installation on Windows was very straight forward.

On Linux, it didn't go as smoothly. I will try to troubleshoot the current installation.

If I am not successful, I will revert back to a previous snapshot, and begin from scratch.

Just a note, that before trying to resolve the PostgreSQL install on Linux, I tried opening
both psql & pgAdmin on Windows with the following errors (see below):

psql: could not connect to server: Connection refused (0x0000274D/10061)
        Is the server running on host "localhost" (::1) and accepting
        TCP/IP connections on port 5432?
could not connect to server: Connection refused (0x0000274D/10061)
        Is the server running on host "localhost" (127.0.0.1) and accepting
        TCP/IP connections on port 5432? 

& 
pgAdmin: Connect to Server
could not connect to server: Connection refused (0x0000274D/10061) Is the server running on host "localhost" (::1) and accepting TCP/IP connections on port 5432? could not connect to server: Connection refused (0x0000274D/10061) Is the server running on host "localhost" (127.0.0.1) and accepting TCP/IP connections on port 5432?

So, I disabled both the Windows Firewall & Avast's Shield Control, but with no success.

Same errors generated.

Sunday will be my day to troubleshoot PostgreSQL prior to going through the Django & PostgreSQL Tutorials.

After uploading my Django Learning Log App to Heroku, I realized that it would be nice to be able to maintain some test data in production, if need be.

Unfortunately, Django's default database is SQLite3 and Heroku's is PostgreSQL. Therefore, all data is lost during app migration to Heroku.

My plan is to:
a.install PostgreSQL locally (Windows & Linux)
b.migrate the existing SQLite3 databases to PostgreSQL (for both apps: "Learning Log" & "Blog")
c.re-deploy Learning Log to Heroku to confirm test data presence
d.deploy Blog to Heroku to confirm test data presence
e.set PostgreSQL as Django's default database moving forward

Possible Enhancements for Django Apps (Learning Log & Blog)

1.add delete functionality to apps:
  a.learning log: topics & entries
  b.blog: blogposts

2.look for sample learning log structures

3.implement sub-topics (like sub-categories)
 
4.based on #3, maybe provide user option to make as many sub-levels as desired???

5.provide user with ability to choose either private or public learning log / blog???
    see Python Crash Course (last exercises)
6.how are normal blogs structured? 
	are there private sides? as well as, public sides?
7.biliangual
8.multilingual
9.theme selection

While improving my apps, remember that on Linux I will be able to use the
gunicorn server locally for testing. 

Refer to Python Crash Course:

	Using the gunicorn Server Locally p.470 (use C7-SRV2)

PostgreSQL is a Windows service and that service, "postgresql-x64-9.6", is set to start automatically. 

Unfortunately, this morning, it wasn't running because yesterday I issued the following Powershell command:

Get-Process postgres | Stop-Process

And, I didn't reboot !!!

Remember, SERVICE MUST BE RUNNING !!!

Powershell command: Get-Process postgres, MUST RETURN SOMETHING!!!

Now onto my troubleshooting of PostgreSQL on Linux....

I'm searching and trying to compile a list of steps to perform in order to successfully install PostgreSQL 9.6, along with pgAdmin4. (based on the steps listed on the sites I've found) 

Almost there....

Now, VirtualBox is giving me problems. hmm, never easy....

For Centos 7, in order to update to the newest kernel, my /boot partition needs to be extended.

Unfortunately, it's not LVM, which makes life easy. Going to try and boot into GParted and do some magic....

Hope it works! 

If not, once again, I'll have to revert back to an old snapshot. Then, I'll install the newer version of VirtualBox (5.22), add the Extension Pack & update Guest Additions.

Finally, I'll update my CentOS system and install PostgreSQL & pgAdmin. Fingers are crossed !!!

***NOTE: if all else fails, follow steps here -> https://access.redhat.com/discussions/3060611

Looks like I'm going to revert back to an old snapshot and start over.

Moving forward, must increase the size of my /boot directory to between 1-2 GB.

Hopefully, I can still perform all my immediate testing using C7-SRV2 with a /boot size of 250MB.

Successfully installed PostgreSQL 11.1 on Centos 7.

Followed the steps listed at https://domalab.com/install-postgresql-pgadmin-linux-centos/

Can now use PostgreSQL as my database server for my Django apps.

Have access to both "psql" & "pgAdmin4" for database management.

I chose the wrong tutorial to follow for my test deployment of a Django app to Heroku.

I need to learn more about the inner workings of Heroku, in order to be able to troubleshoot
deployment issues & failures.

A little at a time...

My next step, for Heroku, will be to watch the Codemy.com video series.

(see E:\IT\1a-PROGRAMMING\DJANGO\HEROKU\How To Push Django Python Apps To Heroku for Web Hosting\)

In the series, we build an app and deploy it to Heroku, while learning about Heroku itself.

Need to find out how to convert an existing SQLite3 database for a Django app to PostgreSQL.

Will do some research and testing. Then, I'd like to perform a database conversion and Heroku deployment 
to confirm that my local PostgreSQL database data can be migrated to Heroku.

For steps, see Desktop\DEC-20.txt

After completing the Django db migration and Heroku deployment (using my Django Blog app), I would like to perform 
the same for my Django Learning Log app.

Then, I can work on improving my Learning Log app:

a.option to make topic public (private by default)
b.add option for sub-topics (maybe...)
AND/OR
b.task list associated with each entry (investigate!!!)
c.make it bilingual (English & French versions of each page)
d.theme selection
e.spelling and/or grammar checking of entries

Finally, after making some minor changes to Learning Log, I can move onto the following:

a.Django / Python FullStack video series
b.Python Network Programming video series & book/s
c.Cisco (need to revisit)

***NOTE: Need to create personal website and find ways to show / present my skills & knowledge using::
  i.videos
 ii.step-by-steps
iii.other ???

While learning new things, or refreshing my knowledge about certain topics, I need to use all the step-by-steps that I create and
make them available on my personal website.

That will be like killing 2 birds with 1 stone:

Becoming better and at the same time sharing what I learn, and/or know, will provide me with lots of content for my site.

Need to investigate how I can incorporate a task list into my Learning Log app.

Associate the task list with a specific Topic? Entry?

Which program/s do the same thing?

Been going through the videos mentioned in my last entry for Heroku.
Really enjoying the videos. John Elder is very good. Straight forward, clear and concise.
a.Successfully created the local Django app (address_book)
b.Created a local git repo
c.Created a Heroku app
d.Made many settings changes on local Django app for smooth migration to Heroku
d.Pushed the local Django app to Heroku
e.Made further settings changes to local Django app to access the Heroku database during local dev testing
f.Will build/enhance local Django app and push changes to Heroku

I am very happy that I am taking this approach to become a little more comfortable with Heroku before 
moving forward, and improving, with my Django development skills.

Just found out how to run multiple instances of Django web server using different ports.

Now I can keep track of what I am learning, when I am working on my Django dev testing, by 
making entries in my Learning Log.
Django
Django FullStack
Python Network Programming
PostgreSQL
Heroku
